<br>
<B>Pickup Raids</b><br>
<br>
1.  Make a list of all interested participants for the raid.  (I actually have forms I produced to help list all the people for the raid.)<br>
2.  Choose a person to be Lotto Master and Rep Leader. (I was able to handle all but some people would feel more comfortable handing out these duties.)<br>
3.  Either you or someone of your choosing needs to be doing a /who all cleric 52 (52 = level of cleric you are looking for) to help determine if the zone you are interested in raiding is occupied.  This will enable you to determine if the zone is occupied by seeing if a cleric is there.  Saves alot of headaches for changing raiding plans due to occupied zone.<br>
4.  Make sure all interested parties are aware of the day, time and location of said raid.  <b>Be adamant about showing up on time.</b>  (I tell them I start forming raid 1/2 hr prior to raid and no shows by 15 min prior to raid will be replaced.  My raids go on time - period.)<br>
5.  Based on the response to your post, you should have some semblance of groups already formed.  If truly a pickup raid (say for Naggy) then start listing those interested and forming your groups.  (I also produced group sheets that I use to track who is in what group and so on.)<br>
6.  Now this part has changed since we have channels.  (Actually much easier IMO.)  Have a raid channel set up in advance.  Assign mod rights to 2-3 people (this is to help with LD of any moderators during the raid.)  Moderate the channel and give voice rights to only the following:  Group Leaders, Lotto Master, MA (2nd assist if you have one), Mezzer, Slower, and any others that may have important jobs within the raid.<br>
7.  Once setup, begin going over all the raid policies.  BE SPECIFIC.  This is your chance to inform the raid of your expectations, rules, conducts mishaps etc.  When I was doing RBL Raids here is mostly what I told them:  a)  All tradeable items will be lottoed at the end of the raid (this helps keep people there to the end.); b) Be specific on lotto rules and who is allowed to roll on said items; c)  Only tells should be from group leaders - if you have something to say... say it to your group leader; d) All junk and gems will come to me (I provided all the dots, stones etc for the raids) until I am reimbursed completely then the rest (gems) will be lottoed at the end of the raid; e) misconduct will not be tolerated; f) if zone is camped (hopefully by now you know if it is or not), we will be moving to ?????; g) make sure everyone understands your commands. (i.e. Camping cleric - who have you assigned to camp out?, Split - who are your two split tanks for multiple mobs if not mezzing?)<br>
<br>
<b>Guild Raids</b><br>
<br>
Very similar to steps listed above with a few minor changes.  After so many guild raids with basically the same individuals attending, all guild members know the rules and policies.  This tep can be omitted.  Also (as I do in my guild) I have people designated to look for clerics in zones by char level to determine if zone is camped prior to raid forming.  <br>
<br>
As most guilds have websites or ezboard forums, make your list of your groups based on the individuals who signed up for the raid on your board or website.  Get things going ahead of logging into game.  Will save you many headaches.  <br>
<br>
Your guild policies may vary from the "pickup raid" policies that you set forth.  That is an internal choice based on your guild needs.  Triad of Honor is NBG and we adhere to much of that even in "pickup raids".<br>
<br>
<b>Raid Leader</b><br>
<br>
There are certain responsibilities that being a raid leader entails.  <br>
<br>
1.  Always commend your raid.  Compliment them.  "Great work" goes a long way.  Even if you wipe out, thank the CR team, the clerics, the mana team etc.  You want to encourage your raid to continue.  Make sure they understand that you recognize their efforts and how they pay off.<br>
2.  Don't change your decisions in mid-stream.  This will only defeat your authority over the raiding party.  Stick to your guns when it comes to your loot policies, raiding tactics etc.  <br>
3.  Be more than fair and honest to your raid.  They will respect you more as time goes on.<br>
4.  Always check  status of your groups.  I always am asking "Group Leader Status Please".  This lets you know who is afk, who is lom, who is ld to help you determine the direction the raid needs to go.  Your MA will become your #1 right hand person.  They are the ones really out in the field, so-to-speak, and amidst the actual fighting/battle of the raid.  Make your decisions are based on what their assessment of the situation.<br>
5.  Make sure your instructions are clear and precise.  REPEAT your instructions many times to ensure that all in the raid see them and understand.  <br>
6.  Do not make any moves during your raid if you have AFK individuals.  Announce when you are moving many times.  If you plan on moving shortly after you have moved to a spot in zone... announce it and also state NO AFKs during that time.  This helps to keep everyone together and you don't lose any members while moving.<br>
7.  If at all possible..... post maps, mob lists, drop lists on your message thread for the raid.  This, however, is not an option when doing pickup raids in game.  You, as Raid Leader, can have this information printed out even when doing a pickup raid in game. <br>
8.  When raid is completed, do not do end of raid lottos in zone.  I take my raiding party to Lavastorm and holds the lottos there.  <br>
9.  As Raid Leader, best be sure to be the last person to gate out of the zone.  This shows your concern for the safety of those who attended your raid.<br>
<br>
I know there is much more to be covered with this topic.  I hope that I have given you a few points to consider when leading raids.  If you have any questions or want to talk about specifics, please give me a tell in the game and I will be more than happy to help you.      <p><img src=http://home.kscable.com/toh/graphics/Shabbate.jpg>"May the wind always be at your back."<br><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=149395">Magelo Profile</a>
