<br>
Brings up another point.  Don't show favoritism in any way.  People don't mind you being an asshole (so long as the raid is going well, in any case) if you're an asshole to EVERYONE equally.  On the raid, YOU are the dictator-in-chief, not the guild leader, not the guild officers.  This means that the officers and guild leader are temporarily demoted to grunts, just like everyone else, while the raid is going on.  A raid with eight different leaders doesn't go anywhere.<br>
<br>
This doesn't mean, however, that you need to do everything.  I personally don't advise even attempting this.  Let the puller be in charge of the mobs to pull, when to move, etc.  Let the MT/MA decide which mobs to attack first, and all that other shiz that melees do.  Let the classes do their job.  They've been playing the game for however many levels now, and they know what's expected of them (or should).  I suppose this is called delegating responsibility.  It doesn't hurt to keep up to pace with whatever decisions your delegated leaders are making though, just to stay informed.  The overall knowledge should stand with you.  Know the zone you're raiding, as much as possible, and know the purposes and goals of your raid, and how to go about achieving them.<br>
<br>
So remember, be an asshole if it's necessary.  If you know what you're doing, the raid will end up running relatively smoothely (not always, what would the fun be in that? <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :b --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":b"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ) most of the time, and your raiders will learn that your raids are good ones, no matter how much of a prick you are when you're in &quot;raid leader&quot; mode <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :b --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":b"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> .<br>
